    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1946-09-20T15:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1946-09-20T15:00:00-05:00" n="791"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d791">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">838.51/9–1846</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the Ambassador in Haiti</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Tittmann</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">confidential</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1946-09-20T16:00:00-04:00"
                            >September 20, 1946—4 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>272. <gloss target="#t_Emb1">Emb</gloss>s reports show govt revenues and foreign
                    trade balance highest for many years and Dept sees no justification drastic
                    proposal described <gloss target="#t_urtel1">urtel</gloss> 384 Sept 18.<note
                        n="65" xml:id="d791fn1">Not printed; in it Ambassador Tittmann reported on
                        receipt of a note of September 16 from the Haitian Foreign Minister
                        describing Haitian financial and economic situations and requesting a
                        moratorium for the coming fiscal year on the 1922 loan, as well as J. G.
                        White and <gloss target="#t_SHADA1">SHADA</gloss> obligations
                        (838.51/9–1846).</note> Please advise Foreign Minister informally Dept knows
                    no reason Haiti should not make necessary arrangements meet contractual
                    obligations in full except when specific arrangements previously made with
                    creditors for departure from that principle, pursuant practice past years. This
                    practice in case of <pb facs="0952" n="934" xml:id="pg_934"/> 6 percent bonds
                    described <gloss target="#t_Deptel1">Deptel</gloss> 264 Sept. 13.<note n="66"
                        xml:id="d791fn2">Not printed.</note> Instructions for formal reply will be
                    transmitted to Embassy upon receipt of Haitian note.</p>
                <p>
                    <gloss target="#t_Emb1">Emb</gloss> also requested inquire whether global budget
                    mentioned urgram 321 Sept 10<note n="66" xml:id="d791fn3">Not printed.</note>
                    includes expenditures for amortizations. Dept believes these amts should
                    properly be included, pursuant article 5 para (<hi rend="italic">a</hi>)
                    Executive Agreement Sept 13, 1941.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Clayton</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
